rca 1455","1440":"1440","15 January 1432":"15 januari 1432","1493":"1493","Radbourne, Warwickshire, England":"Radbourne, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England","South Mills, Blunham, bedfordshire, England":"South Mills, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1400–1493":"1400–1493","1432–1497":"1432–1497","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1455–1498":"1455–1498","–Male":"Deceased","ABT 1440":"about 1440","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1498":"1498","1432":"1432","1497":"1497","ABT 1443":"about 1443","ABT 1455":"about 1455","1440":"1440","15 January 1432":"15 January 1432","1493":"1493","Radbourne, Warwickshire, England":"Radbourne, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","South Mills, Blunham, bedfordshire, England":"South Mills, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hodnell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hudnall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hudnall","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hudnall, hamlet in Little Gaddesden, Hertfordshire, named from the Old English personal name <i>Hūda</i> (genitive <i>Hūdan</i>) + Old English <i>healh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’.","History: In <i>c.</i> 1635, John Hudnall (born in 1616) emigrated to Isle of Wight County, VA. He was probably a descendant of Henry de Hodenhale, who is recorded in the neighborhood of Little Gaddesden, Hertfordshire, in 1307. The surname recurs in that village until the early 17th century and in nearby towns until the early 19th century, but it has since disappeared from English records."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"John of Hodnell de Spencer married Lady Mary Agnes Warsted about 1443, in Hodnell, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1400–1493":"1400–1493","1432–1497":"1432–1497","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1455–1498":"1455–1498","–Male":"Surnud","ABT 1440":"umbes 1440","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1498":"1498","1432":"1432","1497":"1497","ABT 1443":"umbes 1443","ABT 1455":"umbes 1455","1440":"1440","15 January 1432":"15. jaanuar 1432","1493":"1493","Radbourne, Warwickshire, England":"Radbourne, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","South Mills, Blunham, bedfordshire, England":"South Mills, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":